And I also really liked the constant play with the camera angle.

author: @Sugarpuff194
text:
Obviously, I donâ€™t know anything about Hoshiâ€™s personal life beyond what he puts forward, nor should any fanâ€¦ but are others getting wonderfully casual bi vibes from this choreo?

- Hoshi says in theâ€œBEHINDâ€ video that â€œthe lyrics mean that Iâ€™m trapped in the other personâ€™s spider web, but that I like being trapped.â€ Both men and women perform trapping moves in every version--whether the dancers are embracing Hoshi or tossing him around, he doesnâ€™t seem disinclined about either. 

- Thereâ€™s the even split of backup dancers wearing white or black shirts. Thatâ€™s one binary. Iâ€™m not entirely certain what the black/white represents (style of attraction?), but itâ€™s reasonable to assume that that was a choice. Now, I donâ€™t know a thing about how bisexuality is represented in Korea, but Hoshiâ€™s outfits (either gray or black-and-white by version) suggest to me that, for the video, he embodies both opposing ends of a binary and exists somewhere in the middle.

- We see him caught in the middle again when the dancers make their web formations. The men block the front of the pull-up bar tunnel (0:34) and the women block the back (3:30). Hoshi becomes physically positioned between two opposing ends.

- Just a small detail: in the chorus, we see one move distinctly repeated. It comes first while Hoshiâ€™s among women (0:57) and then later again with the men (2:16). This repeat, the vocal affirmation of â€œyeah,â€ and the general thottiness of the move collectively feels significant, at least to me.

- Also, in the â€œM COUNTDOWNâ€ version, the dancers all wear gender-obscuring masks, which is interesting. The intro shows Hoshi acting on desire with a group, where he gives no visible preference to anyone. He embraces the entire group by tying their hands, â€œtrappingâ€ them the way theyâ€™ve â€œtrappedâ€ him.

Again, Hoshiâ€™s sexuality is his business, unless he puts anything forth stating otherwise. I canâ€™t imagine the potential trauma of being a queer man in the kpop industry, and I donâ€™t take the discussion lightly. However, I find the possibility of queer artistry being represented here really exciting and brave as hell. In short, Hoshiâ€™s moves are astonishing, this performance is INCREDIBLY creative, and of course: Horanghae

Tbh it might even claim its position as the best dance choreography to have come out in the past 2 years.

author: @kakaobaecker1511
text:
This performance is gold.
I often don't like the use of backup dancers in Kpop - when the stage is crowded with people dancing the same choreography as the idol and sometimes equally as good (they are professional dancers after all), just to fill the stage. In my opinion, that doesn't feel necessary and makes the idol stand out less.

But these aren't used as "backup" dancers, they are important to the choreography! So many amazing, smart and new formations - and Hoshi being the protagonist of the performance! 
And tbh, with his skills and stage presence he TOTALLY still stands out while doing the same moves as everyone else...damn he could tie his shoe and I'd think it was part of the performance lol

Shoutout to the dancers too. They were killing it. This choreo wouldn't work if they weren't fully committed to the performance quality in their bodies and each one of them completely goes for it.
